#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:158
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mounting A Drive or Filesystem For Backup"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:161
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this step, we show how to mount a hard drive, such as an external USB hard drive, that will be used to back up your system. This particular step is only necessary if you are backing up a single machine or server, as seen in our first example below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:163
#, no-wrap
msgid "Plug in the USB drive.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:163
#, no-wrap
msgid "Type `dmesg | grep sd` which should show you the drive you want to use. In this case, it'll be called _sda1_.  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:165
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Example: `EXT4-fs (sda1): mounting ext2 file system using the ext4 subsystem`.\n"
"3. Unfortunately (or fortunately depending on your opinion) most modern Linux desktop operating systems automount the drive if they can. This means that, depending on various factors, _rsnapshot_ might lose track of the hard drive. We want the drive to \"mount\" or make its files available in the same place every time.  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:172
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To do that, take the drive information revealed in the `dmesg` command above and type `mount | grep sda1`, which should show something like this: `/dev/sda1 on /media/username/8ea89e5e-9291-45c1-961d-99c346a2628a`\n"
"4. Type `sudo umount /dev/sda1` to unmount your external hard drive.\n"
"5. Next, create a new mount point for the backup: `sudo mkdir /mnt/backup`\n"
"6. Now mount the drive to your backup folder location: `sudo mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/backup`\n"
"7. Now type `mount | grep sda1` again, and you should see something like this: `/dev/sda1 on /mnt/backup type ext2 (rw,relatime)`\n"
"8. Next create a directory that must exist for the backup to continue on the mounted drive. We are using a folder called \"storage\" for this example: `sudo mkdir /mnt/backup/storage`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:174
#, no-wrap
msgid "Note that for a single machine, you will have to either repeat the `umount` and `mount` steps each time the drive is plugged in again, or each time the system reboots, or automate these commands with a script.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:176
#, no-wrap
msgid "We recommend automation. Automation is the sysadmin way.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:177
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring rsnapshot"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:180
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is the most important step. It's easy to make a mistake when making changes to the configuration file. The _rsnapshot_ configuration requires tabs for any separation between elements, and a warning to that effect is at the very top of the configuration file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:182
#, no-wrap
msgid "A space character will cause the entire configuration—and your backup—to fail. For instance, near the top of the configuration file is a section for the `# SNAPSHOT ROOT DIRECTORY #`. If you were adding this in from scratch, you would type `snapshot_root` then TAB and then type `/whatever_the_path_to_the_snapshot_root_will_be/`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:184
#, no-wrap
msgid "The best thing is that the default configuration that comes with _rsnapshot_ only needs minor changes to make it work for a backup of a local machine. It's always a good idea, though, to make a backup copy of the configuration file before you start editing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:186
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cp /etc/rsnapshot.conf /etc/rsnapshot.conf.bak`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:187
#, no-wrap
msgid "Basic Machine or Single Server Backup"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:190
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this case, _rsnapshot_ is going to be run locally to back up a particular machine. In this example, we'll break down the configuration file, and show you exactly what you need to change.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:192
#, no-wrap
msgid "You will need to use `vi` (or edit with your favorite editor) to open the _/etc/rsnapshot.conf_ file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:194
#, no-wrap
msgid "The first thing to change is the _snapshot_root_ setting which by default has this value:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:196
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:344
#, no-wrap
msgid "`snapshot_root   /.snapshots/`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:198
#, no-wrap
msgid "We need to change this to our mount point that we created above plus the addition of \"storage\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:200
#, no-wrap
msgid "`snapshot_root   /mnt/backup/storage/`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:202
#, no-wrap
msgid "We also want to tell the backup NOT to run if the drive is not mounted. To do this, remove the \"#\" sign (also called a remark, pound sign, number sign, hash symbol, etc.) next to `no_create_root` so that it looks like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:204
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:348
#, no-wrap
msgid "`no_create_root 1`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:206
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next go down to the section titled `# EXTERNAL PROGRAM DEPENDENCIES #` and remove the comment (again, the \"#\" sign) from this line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:208
#, no-wrap
msgid "`#cmd_cp         /usr/bin/cp`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:210
#, no-wrap
msgid "So that it now reads:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:212
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cmd_cp         /usr/bin/cp`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:214
#, no-wrap
msgid "While we do not need `cmd_ssh` for this particular configuration, we will need it for our other option below and it doesn't hurt to have it enabled. So find the line that says:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:216
#, no-wrap
msgid "`#cmd_ssh        /usr/bin/ssh`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:218
#, no-wrap
msgid "And remove the \"#\" sign so that it looks like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:220
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cmd_ssh        /usr/bin/ssh`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:222
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next we need to skip down to the section titled `#     BACKUP LEVELS / INTERVALS         #`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:224
#, no-wrap
msgid "This has been changed from earlier versions of _rsnapshot_ from `hourly, daily, monthly, yearly` to `alpha, beta, gamma, delta`. Which is a bit confusing. What you need to do is add a remark to any interval that you won't be using. In the configuration, delta is already remarked out.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:226
#, no-wrap
msgid "For this example, we aren't going to be running any other increments other than a nightly backup, so just add a remark to alpha and gamma so that the configuration looks like this when you are done:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:227
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#retain  alpha   6\n"
"retain  beta    7\n"
"#retain  gamma   4\n"
"#retain delta   3\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:235
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now skip down to the logfile line, which by default should read:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:237
#, no-wrap
msgid "`#logfile        /var/log/rsnapshot`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:239
#, no-wrap
msgid "And remove the remark so that it is enabled:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:241
#, no-wrap
msgid "`logfile        /var/log/rsnapshot`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:243
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finally, skip down to the `### BACKUP POINTS / SCRIPTS ###` section and add any directories that you want to add in the `# LOCALHOST` section, remember to use TAB rather than SPACE between elements!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:245
#, no-wrap
msgid "For now write your changes (`SHIFT :wq!` for `vi`) and exit the configuration file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:246
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking The Configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:249
#, no-wrap
msgid "We want to make sure that we didn't add spaces or any other glaring errors to our configuration file while we were editing it. To do this, we run _rsnapshot_ against our configuration with the `configtest` option:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:251
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rsnapshot configtest` will show `Syntax OK` if there are no errors in the configuration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:253
#, no-wrap
msgid "You should get into the habit of running `configtest` against a particular configuration. The reason for that will be more evident when we get into the **Multiple Machine or Multiple Server Backups** section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:255
#, no-wrap
msgid "To run `configtest` against a particular configuration file, run it with the -c option to specify the configuration:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:257
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot.conf configtest`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:258
#, no-wrap
msgid "Running The Backup The First Time"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:261
#, no-wrap
msgid "Everything has checked out, so it's time to go ahead and run the backup for the first time. You can run this in test mode first if you like, so that you can see what the backup script is going to do.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:263
#, no-wrap
msgid "Again, to do this you don't necessarily have to specify the configuration in this case, but you should get into the habit of doing so:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:265
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot.conf -t beta`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:267
#, no-wrap
msgid "Which should return something like this, showing you what will happen when the backup is actually run:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:268
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"echo 1441 > /var/run/rsnapshot.pid\n"
"mkdir -m 0755 -p /mnt/backup/storage/beta.0/\n"
"/usr/bin/rsync -a --delete --numeric-ids --relative --delete-excluded \\\n"
"    /home/ /mnt/backup/storage/beta.0/localhost/\n"
"mkdir -m 0755 -p /mnt/backup/storage/beta.0/\n"
"/usr/bin/rsync -a --delete --numeric-ids --relative --delete-excluded /etc/ \\\n"
"    /mnt/backup/storage/beta.0/localhost/\n"
"mkdir -m 0755 -p /mnt/backup/storage/beta.0/\n"
"/usr/bin/rsync -a --delete --numeric-ids --relative --delete-excluded \\\n"
"    /usr/local/ /mnt/backup/storage/beta.0/localhost/\n"
"touch /mnt/backup/storage/beta.0/\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:283
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you are satisfied with the test, go ahead and run it manually the first time without the test:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:285
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot.conf beta`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:287
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the backup finishes, navigate to /mnt/backup and take a look at the directory structure that was created there. There will be a `storage/beta.0/localhost` directory, followed by the directories that you specified to backup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:288
#, no-wrap
msgid "Further Explanation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:291
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each time the backup is run, it will create a new beta increment, 0-6, or 7 days worth of backups. The newest backup will always be beta.0 whereas yesterday's backup will always be beta.1.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:293
#, no-wrap
msgid "The size of each of these backups will appear to take up the same amount (or more) of disk space, but this is because of _rsnapshot's_ use of hard links. To restore files from yesterday's backup, you would simply copy them back from beta.1's directory structure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:295
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each backup is only an incremental backup from the previous run, BUT, because of the use of hard links, each backup directory, contains either the file or the hard-link to the file in whichever directory it was actually backed up in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:297
#, no-wrap
msgid "So to restore files, you don't have to pick and choose which directory or increment to restore them from, just what time stamp the backup should have that you are restoring. It's a great system and uses far less disk space than many other backup solutions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:298
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting The Backup To Run Automatically"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:301
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once everything has been tested and we know that things will work without issue, the next step is to set up the crontab for the root user, so that all of this can be done automatically every day:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:303
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sudo crontab -e`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:305
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you haven't run this before, choose vim.basic as your editor or your own editor preference when the `Select an editor` line comes up.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:307
#, no-wrap
msgid "We are going to set our backup to automatically run at 11 PM, so we will add this to the crontab:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:308
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"## Running the backup at 11 PM\n"
"00 23 *  *  *  /usr/bin/rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot.conf beta`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:313
#, no-wrap
msgid "Multiple Machine or Multiple Server Backups"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:316
#, no-wrap
msgid "Doing backups of multiple machines from a machine with a RAID array or large storage capacity, either on premises or from across the Internet works very well.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:318
#, no-wrap
msgid "If running these backups from across the Internet, you need to make sure that both locations have adequate bandwidth for the backups to occur. You can use _rsnapshot_ to synchronize an on-site server with an off-site backup array or backup server to improve data redundancy.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:322
#, no-wrap
msgid "We are assuming that you are running _rsnapshot_ from a machine remotely, on-premise. This exact configuration can be duplicated, as indicated above, remotely off-premise as well.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:324
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this case, you will want to install _rsnapshot_ on the machine that is doing all of the backups. We are also assuming:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:328
#, no-wrap
msgid "That the servers you will be backing up to, have a firewall rule that allows the remote machine to SSH into it\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:328
#, no-wrap
msgid "That each server that you will be backing up has a recent version of `rsync` installed. For Rocky Linux servers, run `dnf install rsync` to update your system's version of `rsync`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:328
#, no-wrap
msgid "That you've either connected to the machine as the root user, or that you have run `sudo -s` to switch to the root user.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:329
#, no-wrap
msgid "SSH Public / Private Keys"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:332
#, no-wrap
msgid "For the server that will be running the backups, we need to generate an SSH key-pair for use during the backups. For our example, we will be creating RSA keys.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:334
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you already have a set of keys generated, you can skip this step. You can find out by doing an `ls -al .ssh` and looking for an `id_rsa` and `id_rsa.pub` key pair. If none exists, use the following link to set up keys for your machine and the server(s) that you want to access:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:336
#, no-wrap
msgid "[SSH Public Private Key Pairs](../security/ssh_public_private_keys.md)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:337
#, no-wrap
msgid "_rsnapshot_ Configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:340
#, no-wrap
msgid "The configuration file needs to be just like the one we created for the **Basic Machine or Single Server Backup** above, except that we want to change some of the options.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:342
#, no-wrap
msgid "The snapshot root can be reverted back to the default like so:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:346
#, no-wrap
msgid "And this line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:350
#, no-wrap
msgid "... can be commented out again:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:352
#, no-wrap
msgid "`#no_create_root 1`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:354
#, no-wrap
msgid "The other difference here is that each machine will have its very own configuration. Once you get used to this, you'll simply copy one of your existing configuration files over to a new name and then modify it to fit any additional machines that you want to backup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:356
#, no-wrap
msgid "For now, we want to modify the configuration file just like we did above, and then save it. Then copy that file as a template for our first server:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:358
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cp /etc/rsnapshot.conf /etc/rsnapshot_web.conf`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:360
#, no-wrap
msgid "We want to modify the new configuration file and create the log and lockfile with the machine's name:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:362
#, no-wrap
msgid "`logfile /var/log/rsnapshot_web.log`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:364
#, no-wrap
msgid "`lockfile        /var/run/rsnapshot_web.pid`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:366
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next, we want to modify rsnapshot_web.conf so that it includes the directories we want to back up. The only thing that is different here is the target.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:368
#, no-wrap
msgid "Here's an example of the web.ourdomain.com configuration:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:369
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"### BACKUP POINTS / SCRIPTS ###\n"
"backup  root@web.ourourdomain.com:/etc/     web.ourourdomain.com/\n"
"backup  root@web.ourourdomain.com:/var/www/     web.ourourdomain.com/\n"
"backup  root@web.ourdomain.com:/usr/local/     web.ourdomain.com/\n"
"backup  root@web.ourdomain.com:/home/     web.ourdomain.com/\n"
"backup  root@web.ourdomain.com:/root/     web.ourdomain.com/\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:378
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking The Configuration and Running The Initial Backup"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:381
#, no-wrap
msgid "Just like before, we can now check the configuration to make sure it is syntactically correct:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:383
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot_web.conf configtest`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:385
#, no-wrap
msgid "And just like before, we are looking for the `Syntax OK` message. If all is well, we can execute the backup manually:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:387
#, no-wrap
msgid "`/usr/bin/rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot_web.conf beta`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:389
#, no-wrap
msgid "Assuming that everything works alright, we can then create the configuration files for the mail server (rsnapshot_mail.conf) and portal server (rsnapshot_portal.conf), test them, and do a trial backup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:390
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automating The Backup"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:393
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automating backups for the multiple machine/server version is slightly different. We want to create a bash script to call the backups in order. When one finishes the next will start. This script will look something like this and be stored in /usr/local/sbin:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:395
#, no-wrap
msgid "`vi /usr/local/sbin/backup_all`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:397
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the content:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:398
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#!/bin/bash/\n"
"# script to run rsnapshot backups in succession\n"
"/usr/bin/rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot_web.conf beta\n"
"/usr/bin/rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot_mail.conf beta\n"
"/usr/bin/rsnapshot -c /etc/rsnapshot_portal.conf beta\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:406
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then we make the script executable:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:408
#, no-wrap
msgid "`chmod +x /usr/local/sbin/backup_all`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:410
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then create the crontab for root to run the backup script:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsnapshot_backup.md:415
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"## Running the backup at 11 PM\n"
"00 23 *  *  *  /usr/local/sbin/backup_all\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
